The future of space exploration will likely involve reusable spacecraft.Elon Musk is the latest big name to champion reusable vehicles, and he’s also a major proponent of the concept. His company SpaceX is launching reused Falcon 9 rockets now, and he claims that someday it will not be uncommon to see a single vehicle launch five or six rockets per flight.Such a fleet would allow reusable vehicles to be deployed at locations where one may be unable to launch with the proper rockets for a full mission.“We want to leave the core in the earth,” Musk explained at the TED2013 conference last month. “There will never be an orbital highway that is sufficient to put everything into orbit. So what do we want to do? We want to get down to an area where there will never be enough rockets. There are places you can deploy multiple missions in space. We can deploy a very long mission. The Earth is essentially unlimited in terms of launches. The Earth has much smaller launch costs so

