Newton's first law of motion states that an object at rest is acting constantly upon another object. When you accelerate any object you must also add a moment of inertia to overcome. I'm confused as to why you would put weight on one side to resist it.To resist the acceleration, it is simply required that the acceleration is less than initial value at the surfaceRight, right. So if you can move up a hill by walking, how would you walk backwards? Same concept. So why would you want to stick weight on the downhill slope? If you accelerate downward then any weight added must be added at an angle to prevent additional momentum being imparted, right? A downward force for you, right? I'm stupid. I understand now.It's a bit different because of the gradient of the slope, and that is the thing with gravity where your momentum is higher (more momentum) on the upslope. So for a walking object you can really push it down a hill like on the "up" since the momentum is lower.

